{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b3ecab57-d74a-4d34-9141-5ffa51ebaece","content":"The project directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a `dotnet tool`:\n\n### In your `.csproj`, add these properties:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- Required NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points:\n\n1. **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a .NET tool (must be a console app)\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`)\n3. **Stdio transport** works naturally since dotnet tools run as console processes\n\n### Publish steps:\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server  # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimal setup. No special MCP-specific packaging is needed — stdio transport \"just works\" since dotnet tools are console apps with stdin/stdout.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"da5f21ce-f366-4a7c-93e3-480065016db1","outputTokens":462,"requestId":"3C07:20979:200F52A:23F9358:69E81D56"},"id":"d1f57492-e3f5-45cf-8a63-7c65a4fb673a","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:59:11.706Z","parentId":"c102a5e5-7c8a-4c2a-92b9-8e4db432575a"}
